This may not make a difference, but you don&#39;t need to create a function as value for onChange in your TextField components. onChange is going to pass event to your function unless your TextField component isn&#39;t handling that properly. In other words, the usage of the TextField components should look like this...

```
&lt;TextField onChange={titleChange} value={title} /&gt;
```

Your TextField component itself should be doing something like this...

```
function TextField({onChange}) {
    function handleChange(event) {
        // Pass the event as an argument into the onChange prop
        onChange(event) 
    }

    return &lt;input onChange={handleChange} /&gt;
}
```
If your TextField component is a third party component, they do at least pass a value back as an argument so check that.

Another possibility is you are actually mutating todos in the handleAdd function. If you want to insure todos isn&#39;t mutated you can use the ES6 way of adding values to an array...

```
function handleAdd() {
  setTodos([
    ...todos, 
    {
      title: title,
      description: desc
    }
  ])
}
```

If none of that helps console.log your todos state in the parent component and see if it is changing.

 When `component` renders  very first time `todos length` will always `0`. So `{todos.length &amp;&amp;` condition becomes `false`.   

*you should use something like that to avoid this issue :*  

    {todos.length &gt;0  &amp;&amp; &lt;TodoList todos={todos} /&gt;}

I think your handleAdd function should look like this:

    const handleAdd = () =&gt; {
       setTodos(todos =&gt; [...todos, { title: title, description: desc }]);
    };

If the new state is computed using the previous state, you can pass a function to setState:
https://reactjs.org/docs/hooks-reference.html#functional-updates

